2026-04-16 12:33:40 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module relay contacts'] hypothesis_explanation='The power‑to‑control junction shows a healthy ~12 V with correct polarity. Inside the control module, the upstream side of the relay contacts sits at ~11.99 V (battery level) while the downstream side, which feeds the output cables, sits only at ~0.36 V. The same ~0.36 V appears at the load input, confirming that the drop occurs entirely across the relay contacts themselves.\n\nWith the room dark, the relay should be commanded ON and its contacts should act as a near‑short, passing essentially the full 12 V to the load. Instead, almost the entire supply is dropping across the closed contact pair, indicating that the contacts are not making a proper low‑resistance connection. This is consistent with pitted/contaminated contacts, mechanical misalignment, or an internal relay failure, and explains both the original periodic flicker (intermittent contact) and the present state where the lamp is off and only a small residual voltage reaches the load.\n\nTherefore, the faulty component is the relay contact assembly inside the control (ambient sensor) module. Replacing the relay (or the control module containing it) should restore normal operation.'
